  bplus_delete
  bplus_range_scan
  bplus_leaf_scan

  node_page_id
  node_dirty
  node_pin
  node_unpin
  node_cache
}

// Semantic direction:
// btree is a self-balancing search tree where every node has between btree_order/2 and btree_order children.
// btree_order determines the minimum degree; higher order means fewer levels and fewer disk accesses.
// node_capacity is 2*btree_order - 1 keys; node_full triggers a split on insertion.
// node_underflow occurs when a node drops below btree_order/2 keys after deletion, requiring rebalancing.
// key_compare defines the total order used for search and insertion.
// search_lower_bound finds the first key ≥ the search key; used for range scans.
// split_node divides a full node into two and pushes split_median up to the parent.
// root_split creates a new root when the root node is full.
// rotate_left borrows the smallest key from the right sibling via the parent.
// rotate_right borrows the largest key from the left sibling via the parent.
// merge_nodes combines two siblings and the separator key from the parent into one node.
// btree_cursor provides an iterator over key-value pairs in key order.
// cursor_seek positions the cursor at the first key ≥ the target for range iteration.
// bplus_tree stores values only in leaf nodes; internal nodes store only separator keys.
// leaf_chain links all leaf nodes so range scans traverse leaves without ascending.
// bplus_range_scan positions a cursor at the lower bound and follows leaf_chain to the upper bound.
// node_page_id maps each node to a disk page; node_dirty marks nodes needing flush.
// node_pin prevents a node from being evicted from node_cache during a multi-step operation.

// Primitive flow:
// search: start at root -> binary search node_keys -> child pointer if internal -> recurse to leaf
//   leaf: binary search -> found_key or not found
// insert: search to leaf -> insert_non_full or split_node
//   split: split_node -> split_median pushed to parent -> parent may split recursively
//   root overflow: root_split -> new root with single key
// delete: find key -> if leaf: remove; if internal: replace with successor/predecessor
//   underflow: rotate_left/right if sibling has spare keys else merge_nodes
// range scan: bplus_tree -> cursor_seek(lower) -> cursor_next until > upper

// This defines B-tree and B+-tree: node splitting, deletion rebalancing,
// bidirectional cursors, and range scan via linked leaf chains.
